<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">The first process. Everything else in the unit follows from this one.</p>
  <p>Weathering is the rock-breaking step — before anything moves (erosion) and before anything settles (deposition), rocks have to come apart. <strong>Mechanical weathering</strong> (frost wedging, root prying, thermal stress) breaks rock physically; <strong>chemical weathering</strong> (dissolution, oxidation, hydrolysis) changes the rock chemically. In tropical Chennai, chemical weathering dominates — deep, persistent, humid conditions break rock down through chemistry more than through physics.</p>
  <p>Today's anchor question — "<em>what stories does the landscape tell us?</em>" — is the question driving the whole unit. Today we start with the smallest story: how a single rock breaks. By Block 9 you'll be telling the biography of an entire Chennai location.</p>
  <p>This unit also introduces <strong>the Field Geologist</strong> — an AI partner that knows the nine Landscape Biography locations and thinks like someone standing at your site with a notebook. It asks what you observed before it discusses what anything means. Read its opening message on the partner page before your first conversation.</p>
</section>

